File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands.ts, lines 1994-1998

Current code:
```
if (typeof adapter.tools === 'object' && adapter.tools !== null) {
  for (const key of Object.keys(adapter.tools as Record<string, unknown>)) {
    toolNames.push(key);
  }
}
```

The problem: `adapter.tools` is an Array<ToolDefinition> at runtime (confirmed by plugin-sdk/src/index.ts line 52 and the freeze snippet in cli/src/commands/build.ts line 242 which does `Array.isArray(a.tools)`). Object.keys on an array returns string indices ['0', '1', ...], not tool names.

The fix: Replace with array-aware extraction. Since this runs in page MAIN world where types are not available, use defensive runtime checks:

```
if (Array.isArray(adapter.tools)) {
  for (const tool of adapter.tools as Array<Record<string, unknown>>) {
    if (tool && typeof tool === 'object' && typeof tool.name === 'string') {
      toolNames.push(tool.name);
    }
  }
}
```

This matches the actual runtime shape: an array of objects where each has a `name` string property.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands.ts, lines 1758-1760

Current code:
```
if (base64Encoded && isTextMimeType(match.mimeType)) {
  try {
    content = atob(content);
    base64Encoded = false;
  } catch {
```

The problem: `atob()` returns a Latin1 string, which corrupts multi-byte UTF-8 characters. The same codebase already solves this correctly in network-capture.ts lines 204-205:
```
const body = res.base64Encoded
  ? new TextDecoder().decode(Uint8Array.from(atob(res.body), c => c.charCodeAt(0)))
  : res.body;
```

The fix: Replace `content = atob(content)` with:
```
content = new TextDecoder().decode(Uint8Array.from(atob(content), c => c.charCodeAt(0)));
```

This is the canonical pattern for base64 → UTF-8 decoding in browsers. It is already established in this codebase.

File: platform/shared/src/index.ts, lines 322-328

Current code:
```
if (
  host !== '*' &&
  !/^localhost(:\d+)?$/.test(host) &&
  !/^(\*\.)?[a-z0-9]+([-.]?[a-z0-9]+)*\.[a-z]{2,}$/i.test(host)
) {
  return `URL pattern "${pattern}" has an invalid host "${host}"`;
}
```

The fix: Add an IPv4 branch following the existing localhost pattern:
```
if (
  host !== '*' &&
  !/^localhost(:\d+)?$/.test(host) &&
  !/^\d{1,3}(\.\d{1,3}){3}(:\d+)?$/.test(host) &&
  !/^(\*\.)?[a-z0-9]+([-.]?[a-z0-9]+)*\.[a-z]{2,}$/i.test(host)
) {
```

This matches Chrome's native match pattern support for IP addresses. The regex validates the structure (4 dot-separated groups of 1-3 digits, optional port) without fully validating each octet is 0-255 — Chrome itself does not validate octets, so matching Chrome's behavior is correct.

Add tests in platform/shared/src/validation.test.ts in the 'valid patterns' section:
- `*://192.168.1.1/*` should pass
- `https://10.0.0.1:8080/*` should pass
- `*://127.0.0.1/*` should pass

File: platform/shared/src/index.ts, lines 300-302

Current code:
```
const match = pattern.match(/^(\*|https?):/\/(.+?)(\/.*)$/);
if (!match) {
  return `URL pattern "${pattern}" is not a valid Chrome match pattern (expected: <scheme>://<host>/<path>, scheme must be *, http, or https)`;
}
```

The regex requires a path starting with `/`. The pattern `*://example.com` (no trailing slash) is rejected, but the error message doesn't explicitly say the path portion is mandatory.

The fix: Update the error message to be more specific:
```
return `URL pattern "${pattern}" is not a valid Chrome match pattern — expected <scheme>://<host>/<path> where scheme is *, http, or https and path starts with / (e.g., https://example.com/*)`;
```

Check validation.test.ts for any tests that assert the exact error message text and update them to match.
